{"case_facts":"The case involved Millin A. Nobregas (plaintiff) and Virginia Hadad Gonzalez (defendant). From approximately May 2007 through June 2008, Nobregas attended weekly mental health counseling sessions with Gonzalez at her home, paying $60 per session. Gonzalez claimed to have a medical doctorate degree and provided counseling services to Nobregas, who was an attorney and sought counseling on the recommendation of a mutual friend and his ex-girlfriend. Documentation from the Florida Department of Health later issued a Cease and Desist notice to Gonzalez on August 8, 2013, and the Florida Certification Board's records were requested as part of the proceedings.

The relationship became contentious when Gonzalez began counseling Nobregas's ex-girlfriend, Veronica Fazzio, who was the mother of his child. Nobregas alleged that Gonzalez disclosed confidential information from his counseling sessions, while Gonzalez maintained that any information she received either came from third parties or was disclosed in the presence of others. In July 2012, Gonzalez filed a child abuse complaint against Nobregas with the Florida Department of Children and Families, which was dismissed. She also filed a Florida Bar complaint against him alleging assault after her deposition, which was also dismissed.

Nobregas sued Gonzalez for fraud, breach of fiduciary duty, invasion of privacy, negligence, and violation of Florida's Deceptive and Unfair Trade Practices Act. He sought damages for emotional distress, damage to his reputation, interference with his parental rights, and legal defense costs. Medical experts, including Dr. Mark Barnett (psychiatrist) and Dr. Adriana Rosen (Ph.D.), were prepared to testify about Nobregas's mental condition and how Gonzalez's actions caused and aggravated his condition, including the need for new medication. Gonzalez denied most allegations in her answer and raised multiple affirmative defenses, including that Nobregas had given permission to disclose information, that she was privileged to make any alleged disclosures, and that Nobregas's claims should be barred due to unclean hands.","counterclaims":[],"claims":[{"claim_id":"24f43d97-d402-41fd-8989-e4e032ed7c28","raw_texts":["COUNT I - ACTION FOR SEVERE INFLICTION OF EMOTIONAL DISTRESS"],"damages":{"compensatory":["damages greater than $15,000.00 exclusive of interest, attorney fees and costs","monetary damages","damages from privacy breach and disclosure of confidential information","damages for mental pain","damages for increased anxiety, mental anguish, and pain and suffering","damages from defending ongoing paternity action","loss of monies paid to defendant for counseling services","actual damages"],"punitive":["punitive damages"],"statutory":["damages under Florida Deceptive and Unfair Trade Practices Act (FDUTPA)"],"equitable":["equitable relief","declaratory judgment that defendant violated FDUTPA","injunction enjoining future violations of FDUTPA"],"other":["costs","attorney's fees","such other relief that the Court deems just and proper"]},"defenses":[{"name":"Failure to Meet Conditions Precedent","raw_text":"FIRST AFFIRMATIVE DEFENSE - Plaintiff has failed to meet all conditions precedent in bringing these actions. As such, the Plaintiff's action is barred."},{"name":"Wai